Steel production in Japan, the
worldâ€™s second-biggest maker, rose 11.7 percent in September
from a year earlier on demand recovery.  Crude steel output rose to 9.23 million metric tons, the
Japan Iron and Steel Federation said today on its website. The
level is 3.8 percent higher than the previous month, the
statement said.  Production at blast furnaces gained 11.3 percent from a
year earlier to 7.17 million tons, while output from electric-
arc furnaces increased 12.8 percent to 2.06 million tons,
